{"title_page": "Coronavirus Act 2020", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use BrE|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|UK law granting government emergency powers to handle the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{Infobox UK legislation\n|short_title          = Coronavirus Act 2020\n|type                 =Act \n|parliament           = Parliament of the United Kingdom\n|long_title           = An Act to make provision in connection with coronavirus; and for connected purposes.\n|year                 = \n|citation             = 2020 c. 7\n|introduced_by        =\n|introduced_commons   = [[Matt Hancock]], [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]]\n|introduced_lords     = [[James Bethell, 5th Baron Bethell]]\n|territorial_extent   = [[England and Wales]], [[Scotland]], [[Northern Ireland]] (varies by section)\n|royal_assent         = 25 March 2020\n|commencement         = 25 March 2020{{efn|According to sections 87\u201388 of the Act, the Act as a whole commenced on the day it was passed, but various of its specific provisions come into force according to government discretion; national authorities may suspend and revive provisions of the Act.}}\n|repeal_date          = \n|amends               = \n|replaces             = \n|primary_legislation  = \n|amendments           = \n|related_legislation  = [[Civil Contingencies Act 2004]]<br>[[Coronavirus (Scotland) Act 2020]]\n|repealing_legislation= \n|status               = Current\n|original_text        = \n|legislation_history  = \n|use_new_UK-LEG       = yes\n|UK-LEG_title         = \n|revised_text         = \n|theyworkforyou       = \n|millbankhansard      = \n|collapsed            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Coronavirus Act 2020''' is an [[Act of Parliament (UK)|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] that grants the government [[emergency powers]] to handle the [[COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]]. The Act allows the government the discretionary power to limit or suspend public gatherings, to detain individuals suspected to be infected by [[COVID-19]], and to intervene or relax regulations in a range of sectors to limit transmission of the disease, ease the burden on public health services, and assist healthcare workers and the economically affected. Areas covered by the Act include the [[National Health Service]], social care, schools, police, [[Border Force]], local councils, funerals and courts. The Act was introduced to Parliament on 19 March 2020, and passed the [[House of Commons]] without a vote on 23 March, and the [[House of Lords]] on 25 March. The Act subsequently received [[royal assent]] on 25 March 2020.\n\nPoliticians from parties including the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]], and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] demanded closer parliamentary scrutiny of the legislation while it was debated in Parliament. Advocacy groups such as [[Liberty (advocacy group)|Liberty]] and [[Disability Rights UK]] have likewise called for closer examination of the Act and raised concerns over its effects on human rights during and after the pandemic.\n\n==Provisions==\nThe provisions of the Coronavirus Act, which are time-limited for two years, enable the government to restrict or prohibit public gatherings, control or suspend public transport, order businesses such as shops and restaurants to close, temporarily detain people suspected of [[COVID-19]] infection, suspend the operation of ports and airports, enrol medical students and retired healthcare workers in the health services, relax regulations to ease the burden on healthcare services, and assume control of death management in particular local areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/politics/uk-politics/2083492/coronavirus-what-new-powers-will-boris-johnson-have-under-emergency-virus-legislation/|title=Coronavirus: What new powers will Boris Johnson have under emergency virus legislation?|last=O'Donoghue|first=Daniel|newspaper=[[The Press and Journal (Scotland)|The Press and Journal]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-03-18|title=Coronavirus: Emergency laws will give powers to close airports and detain and quarantine people|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-emergency-laws-will-give-powers-to-close-airports-and-detain-and-quarantine-people-11959342|website=[[Sky News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=18 March 2020|title=Government to get right to force people into self-isolation under emergency laws|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-in-the-uk-government-right-force-people-self-isolation-covid-19-outbreak-2482263|newspaper=[[i (newspaper)|i]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Peter |last1=Walker|accessdate=18 March 2020|title=Retired and student medics may be called in to tackle Covid-19 in UK|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/17/retired-and-student-medics-may-be-called-in-to-tackle-covid-19-in-uk|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 March 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=18 March 2020|title=Police allowed to detain infected people under emergency coronavirus laws|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-police-infected-uk-matt-hancock-commons-a9407636.html|date=17 March 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref> The government has stated that these powers may be \"switched on and off\" according to the medical advice it receives.<ref name=\"BBC 19-03-2020\" />\n\nThe Act also provides for measures to combat the economic effects of the pandemic. It includes the power to halt the eviction of tenants, protect emergency volunteers from becoming unemployed, and provide special insurance cover for healthcare staff taking on additional responsibilities.<ref name=\"BBC 19-03-2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51964163|title=Coronavirus: Emergency legislation set out|website=[[BBC News]]|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The government will reimburse the cost of [[statutory sick pay]] for employees affected by COVID-19 to employers, and supermarkets will be required to report supply chain disruptions to the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/uk-lockdown-coronavirus-government-advice-school-closures/|last=Davies|first=Gareth|title=UK coronavirus lockdown plans: What the Government advice means for you|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|url-access=subscription|quotation=Require supermarkets to give the Government information on whether there will be disruptions to their supply chains; Allow employers to claim for the cost of statutory sick pay from the Government where an employee has coronavirus}}</ref>\n\nThe Act formally postpones the [[2021 United Kingdom local elections|local elections originally scheduled for May 2020]] and grants the UK and relevant [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved]] governments the power to postpone any other election, local referendum, or [[recall petition]] until 6 May 2021. Local councillors, [[Directly elected mayors in England and Wales|elected mayors]] and [[Police and crime commissioner|Police and Crime Commissioners]] originally due for election in 2020 will serve three-year terms after their election in 2021, rather than the normal four years, in order to maintain the normal election cycle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-8856/CBP-8856.pdf|title=Coronavirus Bill: Elections|last=Johnston|first=Neil|publisher=House of Commons Library|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|pages=3\u20135}}</ref>\n\n===Time limit and renewal===\nThe Act has a two-year time limit that may be shortened or lengthened by six months at ministerial discretion.<ref name=\"Telegraph-timelimit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/03/19/boris-johnson-news-latest-schools-coronavirus-emergency-bill/|title=Politics latest news: Coronavirus Bill published as government seeks power to force isolations|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|url-access=subscription|quotation=There is also provision for ministers to shorten - or lengthen - this period by six months. ... The Government says that the Bill be debated again in the House of Commons one year after it comes into force.}}</ref> Following a government amendment, the Act is additionally subject to parliamentary renewal every six months.<ref name=\"Independent-sixmonths\" /> It would originally have been returned to Parliament for debate one year after its enactment.<ref name=\"Telegraph-timelimit\" />\n\n==Debate and criticism==\n[[BBC News]] reported on 19 March that there was general agreement in Parliament on the measures contained in the Act, but some MPs had raised criticisms of their extended duration.<ref name=\"BBC 19-03-2020\" /> Conservative backbencher, [[Steve Baker (politician)|Steve Baker]] reluctantly supported the bill but said that it was ushering in a  \"dystopian society\" and urged the government not to allow the measures to continue \"one moment longer\" than necessary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-latest-lockdown-panic-buying-news-cases-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson announces three-week UK lockdown|first1=Tony|last1=Diver|first2=Verity|last2=Bowman|first3=Gareth|last3=Davies|first4=Annelies|last4=Gartner|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>  Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] wrote to Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] on 18 March requesting that MPs be granted a vote to renew the bill every six months,<ref name=\"Independent-renewal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-boris-johnson-uk-government-response-mps-vote-labour-a9410306.html|title=Coronavirus: Labour demands Boris Johnson give MPs votes every six months on emergency powers|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> while Labour MP [[Chris Bryant]] argued that the bill should be subject to renewal every 30 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/some-powers-in-the-coronavirus-bill-are-draconian-and-impinge-on-peoples-liberty|title=Some powers in the Coronavirus Bill are draconian and impinge on people's liberty|last=Bryant|first=Chris|website=PoliticsHome|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The acting leader of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], [[Ed Davey]], also requested that the bill be subject to more frequent parliamentary scrutiny.<ref name=\"Independent-renewal\" />\n\nCommentator Ian Dunt labelled the Act the \"most extensive encroachment on British civil liberties ... ever seen outside of wartime\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politics.co.uk/blogs/2020/03/18/coronavirus-bill-the-biggest-expansion-in-executive-power-we|title=Coronavirus bill: The biggest expansion in executive power we've seen in our lifetime|last=Dunt|first=Ian|website=Politics.co.uk|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The human rights pressure group [[Liberty (advocacy group)|Liberty]] called for closer scrutiny of the bill, raising concerns that significant restrictions on civil liberties could remain in place beyond the end of the pandemic,<ref name=\"libertyhumanrights\">{{cite web|url=https://www.libertyhumanrights.org.uk/news/press-releases-and-statements/liberty-calls-continuous-scrutiny-coronavirus-bill|title=Liberty calls for continuous scrutiny of Coronavirus Bill|website=Liberty|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> and [[Disability Rights UK]] also raised serious concerns about the implications of the Coronavirus Bill on human rights, especially the rights of vulnerable groups, including disabled people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.disabilityrightsuk.org/news/2020/march/suspension-care-act-act-immediately|title=Suspension of the Care Act - act immediately &#124; Disability Rights UK|website=www.disabilityrightsuk.org|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legislative history==\nThe Act was introduced by the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], on 19 March 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-21/coronavirus.html|title=Coronavirus Bill 2019-21|website=www.parliament.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> and passed all remaining stages of consideration in the [[House of Commons]] on 23 March without a vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/emergency-coronavirus-legislation-clears-commons-lockdown-measures-a4395476.html|title=Emergency coronavirus legislation clears Commons as strict lockdown measures introduced across UK|last=Morrison|first=Sean|newspaper=[[The Evening Standard]]|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> It received all stages of consideration in the [[House of Lords]] on 25 March,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2020/march/lords-debates-emergency-covid-19-legislation/|title=Lords debates emergency Covid-19 legislation|website=www.parliament.uk|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> and subsequently received royal assent on 25 March 2020.\n\nConservative MP and former Brexit Secretary [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]] tabled an amendment on 21 March to restrict the time limit of the bill to a \"brick-wall stop\" of one year, threatening a [[Backbencher|backbench]] rebellion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/boris-johnson-faces-commons-rebellion-over-coronavirus-emergency-powers-bill|title=Boris Johnson faces Commons rebellion over coronavirus emergency powers bill|last=Schofield|first=Kevin|website=PoliticsHome|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Conceding to concerns from both Conservative and Labour MPs over infrequent parliamentary scrutiny, on 23 March the government itself amended the bill to require parliamentary renewal of its powers every six months.<ref name=\"Independent-sixmonths\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-emergency-bill-review-boris-johnson-a9418236.html|title=Coronavirus: MPs will review new emergency measures every six months after government relents to pressure|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish Parliament]] agreed a [[Legislative Consent Motion]] on 24 March 2020 for the Act to apply to Scotland. The Scottish Parliament then passed the [[Coronavirus (Scotland) Act 2020]] to regulate the devolved response to the Coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18331534.new-coronavirus-powers-will-brought-immediately-msps-told/|title=New coronavirus powers will be brought in immediately, MSPs told|website=HeraldScotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]]\n*[[Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020]]\n*[[Civil Contingencies Act 2004]]\n*[[Coronavirus (Scotland) Act 2020]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-21/coronavirus.html Coronavirus Act 2020] \u2013 Parliament\n*[https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/coronavirus-bill-what-it-will-do/what-the-coronavirus-bill-will-do Guidance: What the Coronavirus Bill will do] \u2013 Department of Health & Social Care\n*[https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/coronavirus-bill-summary-of-impacts/coronavirus-bill-summary-of-impacts Impact assessment of each clause of the Bill] \u2013 Department of Health & Social Care\n*[https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8857/ Coronavirus Bill Research Briefings] \u2013 House of Commons Library\n*[https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/coronavirus-bill Coronavirus Act 2020] \u2013 [[Institute for Government]] summary\n\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Public health in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 in British law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Acts of Parliament 2020]]\n[[Category:Acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom concerning healthcare]]\n[[Category:Law associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Emergency laws in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Civil rights and liberties in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{use BrE|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|UK law granting government emergency powers to handle the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{Infobox UK legislation\n|short_title          = Coronavirus Act 2020\n|type                 =Act \n|parliament           = Parliament of the United Kingdom\n|long_title           = An Act to make provision in connection with coronavirus; and for connected purposes.\n|year                 = \n|citation             = 2020 c. 7\n|introduced_by        =\n|introduced_commons   = [[Matt Hancock]], [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]]\n|introduced_lords     = [[James Bethell, 5th Baron Bethell]]\n|territorial_extent   = [[England and Wales]], [[Scotland]], [[Northern Ireland]] (varies by section)\n|royal_assent         = 25 March 2020\n|commencement         = 25 March 2020{{efn|According to sections 87\u201388 of the Act, the Act as a whole commenced on the day it was passed, but various of its specific provisions come into force according to government discretion; national authorities may suspend and revive provisions of the Act.}}\n|repeal_date          = \n|amends               = \n|replaces             = \n|primary_legislation  = \n|amendments           = \n|related_legislation  = [[Civil Contingencies Act 2004]]<br>[[Coronavirus (Scotland) Act 2020]]\n|repealing_legislation= \n|status               = Current\n|original_text        = \n|legislation_history  = \n|use_new_UK-LEG       = yes\n|UK-LEG_title         = \n|revised_text         = \n|theyworkforyou       = \n|millbankhansard      = \n|collapsed            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Coronavirus Act 2020''' is an [[Act of Parliament (UK)|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] that grants the government [[emergency powers]] to handle the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|COVID-19 pandemic]]. The Act allows the government the discretionary power to limit or suspend public gatherings, to detain individuals suspected to be infected by [[COVID-19]], and to intervene or relax regulations in a range of sectors to limit transmission of the disease, ease the burden on public health services, and assist healthcare workers and the economically affected. Areas covered by the Act include the [[National Health Service]], social care, schools, police, [[Border Force]], local councils, funerals and courts. The Act was introduced to Parliament on 19 March 2020, and passed the [[House of Commons]] without a vote on 23 March, and the [[House of Lords]] on 25 March. The Act subsequently received [[royal assent]] on 25 March 2020.\n\nPoliticians from parties including the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]], and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] demanded closer parliamentary scrutiny of the legislation while it was debated in Parliament. Advocacy groups such as [[Liberty (advocacy group)|Liberty]] and [[Disability Rights UK]] have likewise called for closer examination of the Act and raised concerns over its effects on human rights during and after the pandemic.\n\n==Provisions==\nThe provisions of the Coronavirus Act, which are time-limited for two years, enable the government to restrict or prohibit public gatherings, control or suspend public transport, order businesses such as shops and restaurants to close, temporarily detain people suspected of [[COVID-19]] infection, suspend the operation of ports and airports, enrol medical students and retired healthcare workers in the health services, relax regulations to ease the burden on healthcare services, and assume control of death management in particular local areas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/news/politics/uk-politics/2083492/coronavirus-what-new-powers-will-boris-johnson-have-under-emergency-virus-legislation/|title=Coronavirus: What new powers will Boris Johnson have under emergency virus legislation?|last=O'Donoghue|first=Daniel|newspaper=[[The Press and Journal (Scotland)|The Press and Journal]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2020-03-18|title=Coronavirus: Emergency laws will give powers to close airports and detain and quarantine people|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-emergency-laws-will-give-powers-to-close-airports-and-detain-and-quarantine-people-11959342|website=[[Sky News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=18 March 2020|title=Government to get right to force people into self-isolation under emergency laws|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/health/coronavirus-in-the-uk-government-right-force-people-self-isolation-covid-19-outbreak-2482263|newspaper=[[i (newspaper)|i]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Peter |last1=Walker|accessdate=18 March 2020|title=Retired and student medics may be called in to tackle Covid-19 in UK|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/17/retired-and-student-medics-may-be-called-in-to-tackle-covid-19-in-uk|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 March 2020|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=18 March 2020|title=Police allowed to detain infected people under emergency coronavirus laws|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-police-infected-uk-matt-hancock-commons-a9407636.html|date=17 March 2020|website=The Independent}}</ref> The government has stated that these powers may be \"switched on and off\" according to the medical advice it receives.<ref name=\"BBC 19-03-2020\" />\n\nThe Act also provides for measures to combat the economic effects of the pandemic. It includes the power to halt the eviction of tenants, protect emergency volunteers from becoming unemployed, and provide special insurance cover for healthcare staff taking on additional responsibilities.<ref name=\"BBC 19-03-2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51964163|title=Coronavirus: Emergency legislation set out|website=[[BBC News]]|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The government will reimburse the cost of [[statutory sick pay]] for employees affected by COVID-19 to employers, and supermarkets will be required to report supply chain disruptions to the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/uk-lockdown-coronavirus-government-advice-school-closures/|last=Davies|first=Gareth|title=UK coronavirus lockdown plans: What the Government advice means for you|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|url-access=subscription|quotation=Require supermarkets to give the Government information on whether there will be disruptions to their supply chains; Allow employers to claim for the cost of statutory sick pay from the Government where an employee has coronavirus}}</ref>\n\nThe Act formally postpones the [[2021 United Kingdom local elections|local elections originally scheduled for May 2020]] and grants the UK and relevant [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved]] governments the power to postpone any other election, local referendum, or [[recall petition]] until 6 May 2021. Local councillors, [[Directly elected mayors in England and Wales|elected mayors]] and [[Police and crime commissioner|Police and Crime Commissioners]] originally due for election in 2020 will serve three-year terms after their election in 2021, rather than the normal four years, in order to maintain the normal election cycle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CBP-8856/CBP-8856.pdf|title=Coronavirus Bill: Elections|last=Johnston|first=Neil|publisher=House of Commons Library|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|pages=3\u20135}}</ref>\n\n===Time limit and renewal===\nThe Act has a two-year time limit that may be shortened or lengthened by six months at ministerial discretion.<ref name=\"Telegraph-timelimit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2020/03/19/boris-johnson-news-latest-schools-coronavirus-emergency-bill/|title=Politics latest news: Coronavirus Bill published as government seeks power to force isolations|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|url-access=subscription|quotation=There is also provision for ministers to shorten - or lengthen - this period by six months. ... The Government says that the Bill be debated again in the House of Commons one year after it comes into force.}}</ref> Following a government amendment, the Act is additionally subject to parliamentary renewal every six months.<ref name=\"Independent-sixmonths\" /> It would originally have been returned to Parliament for debate one year after its enactment.<ref name=\"Telegraph-timelimit\" />\n\n==Debate and criticism==\n[[BBC News]] reported on 19 March that there was general agreement in Parliament on the measures contained in the Act, but some MPs had raised criticisms of their extended duration.<ref name=\"BBC 19-03-2020\" /> Conservative backbencher, [[Steve Baker (politician)|Steve Baker]] reluctantly supported the bill but said that it was ushering in a  \"dystopian society\" and urged the government not to allow the measures to continue \"one moment longer\" than necessary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-latest-lockdown-panic-buying-news-cases-nhs/|title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson announces three-week UK lockdown|first1=Tony|last1=Diver|first2=Verity|last2=Bowman|first3=Gareth|last3=Davies|first4=Annelies|last4=Gartner|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>  Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] wrote to Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] on 18 March requesting that MPs be granted a vote to renew the bill every six months,<ref name=\"Independent-renewal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-boris-johnson-uk-government-response-mps-vote-labour-a9410306.html|title=Coronavirus: Labour demands Boris Johnson give MPs votes every six months on emergency powers|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> while Labour MP [[Chris Bryant]] argued that the bill should be subject to renewal every 30 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/some-powers-in-the-coronavirus-bill-are-draconian-and-impinge-on-peoples-liberty|title=Some powers in the Coronavirus Bill are draconian and impinge on people's liberty|last=Bryant|first=Chris|website=PoliticsHome|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The acting leader of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], [[Ed Davey]], also requested that the bill be subject to more frequent parliamentary scrutiny.<ref name=\"Independent-renewal\" />\n\nCommentator Ian Dunt labelled the Act the \"most extensive encroachment on British civil liberties ... ever seen outside of wartime\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politics.co.uk/blogs/2020/03/18/coronavirus-bill-the-biggest-expansion-in-executive-power-we|title=Coronavirus bill: The biggest expansion in executive power we've seen in our lifetime|last=Dunt|first=Ian|website=Politics.co.uk|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> The human rights pressure group [[Liberty (advocacy group)|Liberty]] called for closer scrutiny of the bill, raising concerns that significant restrictions on civil liberties could remain in place beyond the end of the pandemic,<ref name=\"libertyhumanrights\">{{cite web|url=https://www.libertyhumanrights.org.uk/news/press-releases-and-statements/liberty-calls-continuous-scrutiny-coronavirus-bill|title=Liberty calls for continuous scrutiny of Coronavirus Bill|website=Liberty|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> and [[Disability Rights UK]] also raised serious concerns about the implications of the Coronavirus Bill on human rights, especially the rights of vulnerable groups, including disabled people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.disabilityrightsuk.org/news/2020/march/suspension-care-act-act-immediately|title=Suspension of the Care Act - act immediately &#124; Disability Rights UK|website=www.disabilityrightsuk.org|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legislative history==\nThe Act was introduced by the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], on 19 March 2020,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-21/coronavirus.html|title=Coronavirus Bill 2019-21|website=www.parliament.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref> and passed all remaining stages of consideration in the [[House of Commons]] on 23 March without a vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/emergency-coronavirus-legislation-clears-commons-lockdown-measures-a4395476.html|title=Emergency coronavirus legislation clears Commons as strict lockdown measures introduced across UK|last=Morrison|first=Sean|newspaper=[[The Evening Standard]]|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> It received all stages of consideration in the [[House of Lords]] on 25 March,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2020/march/lords-debates-emergency-covid-19-legislation/|title=Lords debates emergency Covid-19 legislation|website=www.parliament.uk|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> and subsequently received royal assent on 25 March 2020.\n\nConservative MP and former Brexit Secretary [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]] tabled an amendment on 21 March to restrict the time limit of the bill to a \"brick-wall stop\" of one year, threatening a [[Backbencher|backbench]] rebellion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/article/boris-johnson-faces-commons-rebellion-over-coronavirus-emergency-powers-bill|title=Boris Johnson faces Commons rebellion over coronavirus emergency powers bill|last=Schofield|first=Kevin|website=PoliticsHome|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Conceding to concerns from both Conservative and Labour MPs over infrequent parliamentary scrutiny, on 23 March the government itself amended the bill to require parliamentary renewal of its powers every six months.<ref name=\"Independent-sixmonths\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-emergency-bill-review-boris-johnson-a9418236.html|title=Coronavirus: MPs will review new emergency measures every six months after government relents to pressure|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish Parliament]] agreed a [[Legislative Consent Motion]] on 24 March 2020 for the Act to apply to Scotland. The Scottish Parliament then passed the [[Coronavirus (Scotland) Act 2020]] to regulate the devolved response to the Coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/18331534.new-coronavirus-powers-will-brought-immediately-msps-told/|title=New coronavirus powers will be brought in immediately, MSPs told|website=HeraldScotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Health Protection (Coronavirus) Regulations 2020]]\n*[[Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (England) Regulations 2020]]\n*[[Civil Contingencies Act 2004]]\n*[[Coronavirus (Scotland) Act 2020]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2019-21/coronavirus.html Coronavirus Act 2020] \u2013 Parliament\n*[https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/coronavirus-bill-what-it-will-do/what-the-coronavirus-bill-will-do Guidance: What the Coronavirus Bill will do] \u2013 Department of Health & Social Care\n*[https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/coronavirus-bill-summary-of-impacts/coronavirus-bill-summary-of-impacts Impact assessment of each clause of the Bill] \u2013 Department of Health & Social Care\n*[https://commonslibrary.parliament.uk/research-briefings/cbp-8857/ Coronavirus Bill Research Briefings] \u2013 House of Commons Library\n*[https://www.instituteforgovernment.org.uk/explainers/coronavirus-bill Coronavirus Act 2020] \u2013 [[Institute for Government]] summary\n\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Public health in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 in British law]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Acts of Parliament 2020]]\n[[Category:Acts of the Parliament of the United Kingdom concerning healthcare]]\n[[Category:Law associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Emergency laws in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Civil rights and liberties in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "RobertskySemi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:bypass redirect, replaced:Actof theParliament of the United Kingdomthat grants the governmentemergency powersto handle theCOVID-19 pandemic. The A", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_Act_2020"}
